<subSubSection id="C374657AC316FF9FFF419FCF5C704722" pageId="13" pageNumber="390" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BD136F1C316FF9FFF419FCF5F464475" blockId="13.[151,1437,1267,1584]" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C316FF9FFF419FCF5F204401" bold="true" box="[151,307,1267,1293]" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">Distribution:</emphasis>
Known from the Amazonian foothills at the northeastern Andes of 
<collectingCountry id="F3797661C316FF9FFBF19FC85A4E4402" box="[1063,1117,1268,1294]" name="Peru" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">Peru</collectingCountry>
, eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F3797661C316FF9FFB699FCF5B0D4401" box="[1215,1310,1267,1293]" name="Ecuador" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, the mountain range of 
<collectingRegion id="49AAF813C316FF9FFEE59E2B5F94443D" box="[307,391,1303,1329]" country="Venezuela" name="Merida" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">Mérida</collectingRegion>
, the Amazonia in 
<collectingCountry id="F3797661C316FF9FFD8C9E2B5CC3443D" box="[602,720,1303,1329]" name="Venezuela" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
, and in southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="F3797661C316FF9FFC139E2B5A20443D" box="[965,1075,1303,1329]" name="Colombia" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFFF4B00C316FF9FFB929E255B19443E" author="Avila-Pires, T." box="[1092,1290,1303,1332]" pageId="13" pageNumber="390" pagination="1 - 706" refId="ref15408" refString="Avila-Pires, T. (1995) Lizards of Brazilian Amazonia (Reptilia: Squamata). Zoologische Verhandelingen, 299, 1 - 706." type="journal article" year="1995">Ávila-Pires 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFF4B00C316FF9FFACE9E2B5EC74459" author="Rivas, G. A. &amp; Molina, C. R. &amp; Ugueto, G. N. &amp; Barros, T. R. &amp; Barrio-Amoros C. L. &amp; Kok P. J. R." pageId="13" pageNumber="390" pagination="1 - 64" refId="ref18566" refString="Rivas, G. A., Molina, C. R., Ugueto, G. N., Barros, T. R., Barrio-Amoros C. L. &amp; Kok P. J. R. (2012) Reptiles of Venezuela: an updated and commented checklist. Zootaxa, 3211 (1), 1 - 64. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3211.1.1" type="journal article" year="2012">
Rivas 
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C316FF9FFAB49E245B8E443D" box="[1378,1437,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry id="F3797661C316FF9FFEDF9E075F694459" box="[265,378,1339,1365]" name="Colombia" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, this species is distributed in the eastern slope of the Cordillera Oriental and the Amazonian region (
<figureCitation id="13552A74C316FF9FFF389E635F5A4475" box="[238,329,1375,1401]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1888,1912]" captionTargetBox="[217,1370,181,1864]" captionTargetId="figure-22@4.[217,1370,181,1864]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution maps for the cis-Andean microteiid lizards in Colombia (Alopoglossidae + Gymnophthalmidae). Circles are examined specimens, while squares are records from literature (see Supplementary Files for specific references). Red arrows indicate new records for Colombia. Black arrows show a zoom in to regions where several records overlap. The light green shadow indicates the Orinoco River basin, and the dark green the Amazon River basin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5681929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5681929/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD136F1C316FF9FFF119EBF5C704722" blockId="13.[151,1437,1267,1584]" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C316FF9FFF119EBF5F974491" bold="true" box="[199,388,1411,1437]" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">Similar species:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C316FF9FFE5B9EBF5C6D4491" baseAuthorityName="Cope" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[397,638,1411,1437]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Loxopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="390" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="parietalis">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C316FF9FFE5B9EBF5C6D4491" box="[397,638,1411,1437]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">Loxopholis parietalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from other cis-Andean congenerics by the presence of a large fourth pair of chin-shields (reduced in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C316FF9FFD9D9E945CC044CD" baseAuthorityName="Ayala &amp; Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[587,723,1447,1473]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Loxopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="390" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hexalepis">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C316FF9FFD9D9E945CC044CD" box="[587,723,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">L. hexalepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C316FF9FFCDC9E945DD344CD" baseAuthorityName="Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1923" box="[778,960,1448,1473]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Loxopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="390" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="percarinatum">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C316FF9FFCDC9E945DD344CD" box="[778,960,1448,1473]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">L. percarinatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); keeled ventral scales (smooth or weakly keeled in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C316FF9FFED19EF05F8D44E9" baseAuthorityName="Esqueda" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[263,414,1484,1509]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Loxopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="390" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caparensis">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C316FF9FFED19EF05F8D44E9" box="[263,414,1484,1509]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">L. caparensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, smooth in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C316FF9FFDF19EF05CA344E9" baseAuthorityName="Ayala &amp; Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1982" box="[551,688,1483,1509]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Loxopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="390" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hexalepis">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C316FF9FFDF19EF05CA344E9" box="[551,688,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">L. hexalepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); rhomboid dorsals (hexagonal to rectangular with straight lateral margins in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C316FF9FFEC09ECC5FA84705" baseAuthorityName="Avila-Pires" baseAuthorityYear="1995" box="[278,443,1519,1545]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Loxopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="390" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="snethlageae">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C316FF9FFEC09ECC5FA84705" box="[278,443,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">L. snethlageae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); and a large frenocular scale (small frenocular scale in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6E4D72C316FF9FFBEE9ECC5ACF4705" baseAuthorityName="Avila-Pires" baseAuthorityYear="1995" box="[1080,1244,1519,1545]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Loxopholis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="13" pageNumber="390" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="snethlageae">
<emphasis id="B91AEAE3C316FF9FFBEE9ECC5ACF4705" box="[1080,1244,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="390">L. snethlageae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). For a more detailed description see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFFF4B00C316FF9FFE5D9D295C734722" author="Avila-Pires, T." box="[395,608,1555,1584]" pageId="13" pageNumber="390" pagination="1 - 706" refId="ref15408" refString="Avila-Pires, T. (1995) Lizards of Brazilian Amazonia (Reptilia: Squamata). Zoologische Verhandelingen, 299, 1 - 706." type="journal article" year="1995">Ávila-Pires (1995)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
